data.title: Ash Ketchum is gone, but Pok√©mon animation is going stronger than ever
data.meta_description: Pok√©mon was always more than just Ash Ketchum, and with his departure episode on Netflix, we can see all the different places the game and anime franchise can go.
data.text:
The world of Pok√©mon animation, for a long time, always seemed to have two different directives in the wider scheme of the franchise ‚Äî it constantly needed to be both an introduction and an alternative. It had served as a sort of Pikachu-filled warmup in the most literal sense, debuting a few weeks before the Pok√©mon games did in the United States as a teaser taste for the ‚ÄúPok√©mania‚Äù to come. And from then on, with a more obvious focus at younger audiences, it would always be a great way for youngsters to get their feet wet before they jumped into actually taking a role themselves.

Meanwhile, even while serving as a loose adaptation of the games, the journey of Ash Ketchum was filtered through the eternal fourth grader. Even as he served to represent every new kid getting into Pok√©mon for the first time, it was still his story and his lessons to learn. Ash was inextricably tied to Pok√©mon‚Äôs animation output.

However, a lot has changed over the past few years, and the evolution and expansion of Pok√©mon‚Äôs animation output has led to it becoming perhaps the most consistently surefooted and diverse pillar of the franchise. Pok√©mon animation has never just been Ash, and a glance over its 25-year existence reveals a smorgasbord of cartoon pocket monsters, many drawn in service of blatant advertising ‚Äî things like teasers for video games or this oddly well-animated commercial for Chef Boyardee. That‚Äôs no longer the case, though, and just by looking at the recent series Paldean Winds, we see a company taking full advantage of a medium‚Äôs potential and the many sections of its ravenous fan base.

Like Twilight Wings, a recent Pok√©mon series that told an anthology of stories set within the Galar region (and featuring characters that players of Pok√©mon Sword and Shield were likely very familiar with), Paldean Winds is another series that takes place in the world of the games and is adjacent to their action. Paldea, the setting of the latest games, Scarlet and Violet, is ripe for this kind of storytelling, and the first episode is charming without leaning too hard on referencing the Nintendo Switch adventures. Central characters from the games, like the battle-hungry Nemona and troubled Arven, are featured here, but the protagonist is an original character that goes through her own emotional arc.

Animation that ties back into the games rather than serving as a substitute isn‚Äôt a new concept. Miniseries that directly adapt portions of the games while illuminating (or inventing) certain new details have been a staple since 2013. Pok√©mon Origins told an abridged version of the story of Pok√©mon Red and Green, the first Pok√©mon titles, while also highlighting some updated features from the new (at the time) Pok√©mon X and Y. In 2016, Pok√©mon Generations would tackle 18 stories set across six Pok√©mon ‚Äúgenerations,‚Äù with many revealing a kind of ‚Äúuntold‚Äù portion of part of the games‚Äô narratives.

For instance, the third episode, ‚ÄúThe Challenger,‚Äù displayed how your rival from Red and Blue trounced the Elite Four in order to become the final boss of the game. The fifth episode, ‚ÄúThe Legacy,‚Äù dove into the backstory of angsty Silver, your rival from Pok√©mon Gold and Silver, and his relationship with Giovanni, Team Rocket‚Äôs boss and his father. It‚Äôs the kind of thing that, since 1996, fans have spent countless hours theorizing about, gluing little bits of lore together to find a wider picture. To see it animated is surely a present, but it shows Pok√©mon‚Äôs dedication to its own mythology. It‚Äôs an acknowledgment of a thing that hardcore fans already know ‚Äî there are much deeper roots to these stories than just ‚ÄúGotta catch ‚Äôem all.‚Äù

Evolutions worked in similar ways, elaborating on the world of the games, and Hisuian Snow dropped little background hints that connected to the prequel game Pok√©mon Legends: Arceus. These series tend to assume that the audience has already played the games as a precursor, but they‚Äôre often so lavishly produced (Evolutions and Twilight Wings, especially, are absolutely gorgeous, with movie-quality direction) that one doesn‚Äôt necessarily need to experience other Pok√©mon titles to enjoy them. Like Paldean Winds, they‚Äôre full of Easter eggs, but that‚Äôs rarely the main draw. Instead, for episodes like Evolutions‚Äô ‚ÄúThe Show,‚Äù they‚Äôre a chance to bask in a fully formed world that, for many, previously only existed within the 8-bit realm of a Game Boy.

Animation aimed at new fans who weren‚Äôt around when you traded with a link cable has proliferated, too. There is variety of styles of display in Pok√©toon (‚ÄúScraggy and Mimikyu‚Äù resembles 1940s ‚Äúrubber hose‚Äù animation, ‚ÄúThe Pancham Who Wants to Be a Hero‚Äù looks akin to a storybook, and ‚ÄúWait for Me, Magikarp!‚Äù is a dialogue-less, music-driven triumph), while Bidoof‚Äôs Big Stand is pure slapstick. The recent Path to the Peak takes place in the real world, with a main character that desperately wants to become good at the Pok√©mon Trading Card Game. Thankfully, it‚Äôs vibrant enough that even its more commercial elements get lost in a young girl‚Äôs quest to find a hobby (and community) to feel a part of.

One might think that these series correlate with Ash Ketchum being put out to pasture as Pok√©mon‚Äôs leading anime figure (in Japan, the main anime has been replaced by Pok√©mon Horizons, a region-hopping series with new protagonists, though the series hasn‚Äôt yet debuted in the U.S.). But even the final few episodes of Ash‚Äôs journey, ones labeled ‚ÄúTo Be a Pok√©mon Master,‚Äù relish in a relaxed sense of storytelling that is far more low-key than the flashy climax of his recent world championship win. Instead, with former companions Brock and Misty at his side, he embarks on the kinds of episodic odysseys that marked the late ‚Äô90s. It diverts from expectations, instead favoring a comfy victory lap for those that have stuck by Ash for this long. Years ago, it would‚Äôve seemed like a character sputtering out in his last days, but when compared to the recent ambition of other animated series, it becomes one more singular offering.

The move to fully 3D games and a true open-world experience has occurred simultaneously with these changes in Pok√©mon animation. But this transition has been marked by signs of pushed limits ‚Äî in the days following its release, Scarlet and Violet became just as well known for funny glitches that players encountered as the breezy sense of exploration that they offered. In both the developmental side and in regard to player experience, the games seem to be in the midst of intense growing pains. For so long, the games felt like the confident nucleus of the Pok√©mon cell, but Scarlet and Violet proved that they still remain ripe for perfecting and even reinvention.

Pok√©mon animation, on the other hand, is providing a wider spectrum of opportunity for its audience than ever before. Never has there been this many options, and no longer is it defined by one character or how much it differs from the games. Instead, it places value on both Pok√©mon veterans and newcomers, taking the former theme song verse of ‚ÄúWe all live in a Pok√©mon world‚Äù and running with it.
